      Reviewed in the United States on February 13, 2025
      Size: 4 PackColor: Black
      There are quite a few reviewers here who experience problems with this switch. And frankly I lost a couple of hours installing this too, was experiencing similar problems like those people, but then I figured, hmm, maybe I should read the manual :) And then I had it hooked... See more
      There are quite a few reviewers here who experience problems with this switch. And frankly I lost a couple of hours installing this too, was experiencing similar problems like those people, but then I figured, hmm, maybe I should read the manual :) And then I had it hooked up quickly and it works perfectly. I even have it working in a 4way situation too. Once you understand how it works it's easy.

      I felt that the manual was actually quite good, but maybe this will help others:
      When you have a 3way situation, so 2 switches manipulating the same lights, you need to realize that one of those switches is connected to your breaker box, then that swich is connected to the next switch and then that 2nd switch connects to the light. So the power flows from your breaker through switch 1, then switch 2 and then arrives at your lights. You'll first need to determine which switch is which, so which of the 2 connects to the light and which of the 2 connects to the breakerbox. The manual explains quite well how to do that. If you check your standard 3way (dumb) switch you'll see a black screw. This is where the power comes in. So this means that the switch connected to your breaker box connects the power there. Then, the switch sends the power over 1 of the 2 'traveller' lines to the other switch. And then via those traveller lines it ends up at the black screw in that 2nd switch and then goes to the light bulb.

      Now this smart switch works differently! It actually functions much more like a normal switch in a certain matter: it needs a constant line pulse (so not switched/conditionally!) and when you press the switch it changes the output from on to off or from off to on. So you need to rewire the system, you'll rewire one of the 2 travellers so that that traveller ALWAYS becomes hot, so one traveller will be connected 'directly' to your breakerbox. So the other traveller remains. So the smart switch is connected to the light and the old dumb switch is connected to the breaker box. So since the smart switch always will receive a hot line, it will just switch the output (change the bulb on/off) when you press its button. But it will also change the output on/off when it receives a change on/off on the remaining traveller line. So the old (dumb) swith is just used to flip that traveller line. So the smart switch changes on/off by either:
      1) pressing it directly
      2) pressing the old dumb switch, since this will flip the traveller line status, the smart switch will detect it and change the output.

      So once all this gets clear, installation becomes very easy and you can even connect a 4way situation (3 switches). I did this by keeping the breaker box connected switch the dumb one and replace the other 2 with smart switches. So you'll configure the first 2 like above, so both switches will flip the output line. And then use that output line from that first smart switch as traveller to the 2nd smart switch.

      4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      How to wire in 3 way
      Reviewed in the United States on September 23, 2023
      Size: 10 PackColor: White
      I'm writing this to help anyone else who has bought this and struggled with installing it as a 3 way switch. So here goes: The original 3 way will have 3 wires connected and maybe a bare copper ground. One of those wires has a black screw. That's the... See more
      I'm writing this to help anyone else who has bought this and struggled with installing it as a 3 way switch. So here goes:

      The original 3 way will have 3 wires connected and maybe a bare copper ground. One of those wires has a black screw. That's the common, meaning the switch connects that terminal to one of the other 2 terminals when it switches. In standard wiring, this is either the line power or the load (the light fixture), depending on which of the 2 3-way switches you're looking at. This switch must be installed on the 3 way switch that has the load connected to the common. You'll be able to tell which one you've got by where the wires are coming from in the electrical box. If all 3 wires are coming from the same bundle, you're looking at the power side, and it won't work. If the red and white wires are coming from the same bundle, but the common wire is coming from a different bundle, you're looking at the load side and that's where you need to be. At least, that's how the electrician wired my house.

      This switch is not a traditional 3 way switch. It uses the other switch as an input to turn the itself on or off. As such, you will only need 2 of the wires from the switch you're replacing.

      Connect the red load wire to the common wire
      Connect the green to ground
      Connect the white to neutral
      Connect the black to line power
      Connect the blue to one of the other 2 wires from the original switch
      Cap the 3rd wire from the original switch

      If you don't have line power or neutral available:
      You can open up the other switch box and use the unused wire to run either neutral or power to the box you need it in. Just so that no one in the future gets electrocuted, use red for power or white for neutral and also make sure that the power you connect to is from the same circuit breaker.

      As for my rating, great switch once it's installed. Locked off a star for terrible instructions.
